      "content": "I apologize for the goblin overload! You are absolutely right; I got carried away with the metaphorical goblin train and forgot to stick to the hard physics you asked for. Let's cut the fluff and get straight to the mechanics of the pitot tube and the airspeed indicator.\n\nHere is how the system actually works:\n\n**How it Works (The Physics)**\nThe pitot tube measures **total pressure** (stagnation pressure). As the aircraft moves forward, the air in front of the tube is brought to a halt, converting its kinetic energy into pressure. This creates a high-pressure zone at the tip of the tube. Simultaneously, the aircraft has **static ports** (usually on the fuselage) that measure the ambient atmospheric pressure surrounding the plane.\n\nThe airspeed indicator (ASI) is a differential pressure gauge. It takes the signal from the pitot tube (total pressure) and subtracts the signal from the static ports (static pressure). This difference is known as **dynamic pressure**. According to Bernoulli's principle, this dynamic pressure is directly proportional to the square of the airspeed. The instrument uses a spring-loaded diaphragm that expands as the pressure difference increases, moving a",
